04213nam a22006375i 9781575066431DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815750664317 a10.1515/97815750664312doi  a(DE-B1597)584207  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBL1605.D66 -- W39 2011eb 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a299.21 aWay, Kenneth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDonkeys in the Biblical World :bCeremony and Symbol /cKenneth Way. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistory, Archaeology, and Culture of the Levant ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1 Introduction -- tChapter 2 The Donkey in Ancient Near Eastern Texts -- tChapter 3 The Donkey in Near Eastern Archaeology -- tChapter 4 The Donkey in Biblical Literature -- tChapter 5 Synthesis -- tAppendix: Equid Terminology -- tBibliography -- tIndexes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this volume, Kenneth Way explores the role of donkeys in the symbolism and ceremonies of the biblical world. His study stands alone in providing a comprehensive examination of donkeys in ancient Near Eastern texts, the archaeological record, and the Hebrew Bible. Way demonstrates that donkeys held a distinct status in the beliefs and rituals of the ancient Near East and especially Canaan-Israel.The focus on ceremony and symbol encompasses social and religious thoughts and practices that are reflected in ancient texts and material culture relating to the donkey. Ceremonial considerations include matters of sacrifice, treaty ratification, consumption, death, burial, "scapegoat" rituals, and foundation deposits; symbolic considerations include matters of characterization, association, function, behavior, and iconographic depiction. However, the distinction between ceremony and symbol is not strict. In many cases, these two categories are symbiotic. The need for this study on donkeys is very apparent in the disciplines that study the biblical world. There is not a single monograph or article that treats this subject comprehensively. Philologists have discussed the meaning of the Amorite phrase "to kill a jackass," and archaeologists have discussed the phenomenon of equid burials. But until now, neither philologists nor archaeologists have attempted to pull together all the ceremonial and symbolic data on donkeys from burials, ancient Near Eastern texts, and the Hebrew Bible. Way's study fills this void.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781575066431zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781575066431423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781575066431.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK